‚öôÔ∏è Steps to implement (EASY practical version)
1Ô∏è‚É£ Install and log in
pip install wandb
wandb login


(You‚Äôll get an API key from your W&B account after signup.)

2Ô∏è‚É£ Add W&B to your training script

Example: train.py

import wandb
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Step 1: Initialize W&B project
wandb.init(project="iris-classification", name="rf-baseline")

# Step 2: Log hyperparameters
config = {
    "n_estimators": 100,
    "max_depth": 3,
    "test_size": 0.2,
}
wandb.config.update(config)

# Step 3: Load data
iris = load_iris()
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    iris.data, iris.target, test_size=config["test_size"], random_state=42
)

# Step 4: Train model
model = RandomForestClassifier(
    n_estimators=config["n_estimators"], max_depth=config["max_depth"], random_state=42
)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Step 5: Log metrics
acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
wandb.log({"accuracy": acc})

print(f"Accuracy: {acc}")

3Ô∏è‚É£ Run the script
python train.py


You‚Äôll see:

Training metrics appear live on your W&B dashboard.

Each run gets saved with all hyperparameters and metrics.

4Ô∏è‚É£ View results

Go to https://wandb.ai
 ‚Üí Your Project ‚Üí ‚Äúiris-classification‚Äù
You‚Äôll see:

Graphs of metrics (accuracy, loss, etc.)

Comparison between multiple runs (if you change parameters)

